SIMD-Friendly Diffusion Experiment Summary

Dataset: `images/sample.png`, 512x512x3, 786432 bytes. Source data: `results/stage_bench.csv` and `results/candidate_schemes.csv`.

## Diffusion Primitive Ranking

| rank | diffusion | MB/s | speedup vs global_chain | dependency model | SIMD fit |
|---:|---|---:|---:|---|---|
| 1 | `multilane_chain_avx2` | 457.83 | 1.94x | lane-local | excellent |
| 2 | `tree_xor_avx2` | 444.48 | 1.88x | logarithmic | excellent |
| 3 | `arx_block_diffusion` | 396.29 | 1.68x | none | excellent |
| 4 | `prefix_xor_avx2` | 348.81 | 1.48x | associative scan | excellent |
| 5 | `block_local_chain` | 292.34 | 1.24x | block-level | good |
| 6 | `bitplane_diffusion` | 275.26 | 1.17x | none | excellent |
| 7 | `reverse_prefix_xor_avx2` | 272.42 | 1.15x | associative scan | excellent |
| 8 | `parallel_prefix` | 263.29 | 1.12x | reduced | medium |
| 9 | `global_chain` | 236.04 | 1.00x | sequential | poor |
| 10 | `arx_prefix_mod256` | 220.71 | 0.94x | prefix sum mod 256 | medium-high |
| 11 | `prefix_tree_reverse` | 162.07 | 0.69x | multi-pass associative | excellent |
| 12 | `stencil_diffusion` | 161.34 | 0.68x | none per round | high |

Key comparisons:
- `global_chain`: 236.04 MB/s, baseline sequential feedback.
- `prefix_xor_avx2`: 348.81 MB/s, 1.48x faster than global chain.
- `multilane_chain_avx2`: 457.83 MB/s, 1.94x faster than global chain.
- `tree_xor_avx2`: 444.48 MB/s, 1.88x faster than global chain.
- `prefix_tree_reverse`: 162.07 MB/s, 0.69x vs global chain, but slower than single-pass primitives because it performs three diffusion passes.

Interpretation: the fastest SIMD-native diffusion variants are `multilane_chain_avx2`, `tree_xor_avx2`, and `arx_block_diffusion`. Prefix-XOR scan is faster than the sequential chain and preserves the closest chaining semantics, but the current implementation still pays carry/reversal overhead. The combined prefix-tree-reverse construction improves the design story but not raw throughput because it is deliberately multi-pass.

## Candidate Pipeline Results

| rank | scheme | MB/s | keygen | permutation | diffusion | dominant cost |
|---:|---|---:|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `Checkerboard-CA-MultilaneTree` | 400.53 | cellular_automata | checkerboard_swaps | multilane_tree | keygen (66.1%) |
| 2 | `Checkerboard-CA-ARX` | 399.16 | cellular_automata | checkerboard_swaps | arx_block | keygen (64.2%) |
| 3 | `CA-Feistel-ARX` | 95.60 | cellular_automata | feistel_index | arx_block | permutation (74.9%) |
| 4 | `Affine-CA-PrefixTree` | 51.13 | cellular_automata | affine_bitplane | prefix_tree_reverse | permutation (68.6%) |
| 5 | `CML-Feistel-Stencil` | 35.42 | cml | feistel_index | stencil | keygen (55.3%) |
| 6 | `Affine-CML-Bitplane` | 34.45 | cml | affine_bitplane | bitplane | keygen (49.7%) |
| 7 | `Hamiltonian-Block-Stencil` | 10.01 | hamiltonian | block_feistel | stencil | keygen (88.3%) |

The new `Checkerboard-CA-MultilaneTree` candidate is the fastest in this run at 400.53 MB/s, slightly ahead of `Checkerboard-CA-ARX`. This supports the idea that lane-local chaining plus tree mixing is a strong SIMD-native alternative to full-image sequential feedback.

The new `Affine-CA-PrefixTree` candidate is much slower at 51.13 MB/s. The bottleneck is not the prefix/tree diffusion alone; the affine byte permutation is expensive in this implementation, and the diffusion is a three-pass construction. It is useful as a research design, but not the fastest engineering choice yet.

## Direct Answer

Yes, the experiment now tests the proposed SIMD-friendly diffusion ideas:
- XOR prefix-scan diffusion: `prefix_xor_avx2` and `reverse_prefix_xor_avx2`.
- Block-local CBC-style diffusion: `block_local_chain`.
- Multi-lane interleaved chaining: `multilane_chain_avx2`.
- ARX prefix-style diffusion: `arx_prefix_mod256`, plus faster `arx_block_diffusion`.
- Tree diffusion: `tree_xor_avx2`.
- Combined prefix/tree/reverse design: `prefix_tree_reverse` and candidate `Affine-CA-PrefixTree`.

## Paper Claim

The strongest claim from this run is: serial XOR feedback can be replaced by associative or lane-local SIMD forms with measurable speedup. Multi-lane chaining and tree diffusion give the best throughput, while prefix-XOR gives the closest semantic link to classic feedback diffusion. A multi-pass prefix/tree/reverse design is defensible cryptographically as a diffusion experiment, but it must be optimized or paired with cheaper permutation to compete on speed.
